segments.text: You were on active duty?
You never got a leave?
Not up to that time, no.
For five years you didn't get any leave?
Well...
Even before you went overseas?
Sure that I had, each year I had a week at a time, something like that, between, between
Transfers of stations, you take a week off.
Okay, now let's continue to make sure everything's working right.
Let's continue, and you were talking about what it was like going to London.
You were going to start talking about that then.
Well, I got six nights, seven days rest from recuperative leave when I transferred from 777 Field Artillery Battalion to 745 Battalion.
and I flew over in a, I think there were four of us from this, from our core artillery flew over an old DC-3.
They came down and picked us up on a dirt landing strip and flew us to London and it was all blackout.
Of course the
It was rest in that you didn't have to keep any hours.
You could sleep as long as you wanted to, and you'd get up when you wanted to, and do what you wanted to.
The Red Cross, the Salvation Army, and the Army, I guess, sponsored tours, guided tours.
The English-speaking Union of London
ran a tour that I went down.
They took a bunch of us down to Canterbury Cathedral.
Oh, that'd be interesting.
It was an all-day trip.
It was about 40, 50 miles down to Canterbury.
And I got to meet the vicar there who was head of the Church of England.
OK, let's continue.
I forget his name, but he was a very, very

inspiring person and of course he gave us a blessing meaning he said a prayer for us it was most most inspiring trip to see this great Cathedral and to meet the head of the Church of England which we think of it as Episcopal Church mother Episcopal Church
Another trip, I took a boat trip up the Thames.
I went through a bunch of their locks.
Their industry uses barges to transport heavy equipment and bulk material like sacks of grain and this kind of thing.
Was this right at the end of the war?
Yeah, this was right at the end of the war.
So they weren't being bombed anymore?
Well, it was always all blackout at night, but there wasn't prolific bombing, let's just say it that way.
Every once in a while?
Every once in a while you'd hear a rocket or something?
They probably were the V2s.
You'd hear a big boom.
But the V2s were a different thing.
They were Hitler's secret enemy, I mean secret weapon.
They would set them, guide them on a course and they would get their range by putting in so many ounces of alcohol in them.
When we were in Belgium, they started bombing Lige, which was a great big American ordnance depot where they had fields and fields of trucks and guns.
And the Germans picked it up and they started bombing with these flea bombs.
The V2s, you mean, the buzz bombs?
The V1 was buzz bombed, called buzz bombs, and the Germans called them flea bombs.
They can't say fly bombs, and that's what they were trying to say, is fly bombs, buzz bombs.
They called them flea bombs.
But anyway, you'd hear the thing coming over, and it was backfiring or propelling itself.
It made a putt, putt, putt, putt business sound.
And when it stopped putting, you knew to get in your hole, because it's coming down.
And if you were within 150, 200 yards of it, well, it'd get you.
As long as you could hear them putting coming to you and going by, you'd say, oh, thank God that one went by.
Or if you hear it coming and said, oh, Lord, let that one keep going, just talking to yourself.
But when they stopped putting, it meant they were coming down.
They didn't fly over 300 or 400 yards high.
and you could knock them down with anti-aircraft, and that's the way the Americans saved Antwerp, was knocking them down.
They put enough artillery in, I mean, anti-aircraft artillery in there to just shoot them out of the sky, because they were vulnerable.
They were a slow-flight thing, and very cumbersome.
This looked like a big bomb with a very short, stubby wing on it.
Flea bombs.
Anyway, they...
They were harassing London with them, and I'm sure two or three nights would fall and you'd hear them.
How'd the English people treat you when you were there?
Oh, very kindly.
They were welcoming you with open arms.
They looked on us as certainly helping them win the war, if not winning the war for them, because they whipped.
They would beat down.
London was, I don't know, 60% destroyed.
And of course, all that did was really re-emphasize their desire to win the war.
It gave them a real incentive to fight back.
But without American help, they'd never made it.
They just couldn't have made it.
And I think at the, I went up in Scotland one time during this trip.
Took a train up there.
My forefathers came from Weems Castle, Scotland, which is across the Firth of Forth from Edinburgh.
Just across the big bay there.
They called them Firths.
I went up there and my grandmother and my mother both wrote me to go up there and see the whole family.
And so I caught the train, went up there, and did get to visit with some Scotsmen on the train.
And one of them expressed to me that I was on that train the day that they announced
the land lease was stopped, terminated.
And this Scotsman, apparently he was a businessman, said that we certainly appreciated the land lease, but it had to come to an end sooner or later.
And the sooner it comes to an end, the better for us.
And he thought it had helped him tremendously, but the sooner we cut it off, the better.
It'd get them back on their own feet.
And so that was the attitude that I experienced.
They tried to take advantage of you and did take advantage of you on prices and all.
A bunch of us were out, been to a picture show, nothing else to do, and went to a picture show and had a few drinks, decided to go eat something before we went to sleep.
It was 10, 30, 11 o'clock at night, and of course it was blackout.
and went and two or three opened doors, and then inside there, they didn't have anything, and they'd say, go on down to about the fourth door there, and this is down around Trafalgar Square.
Piccadilly, they called it.
And we got down there and went down to the fourth door and started down, and a bunch of English girls were coming out.
And I don't know, one of us asked them, we said, is there anything to eat down there?
And they said, yeah, they got some food down there.
So we went on down.
And all they had was, I asked them for scrambled eggs and bacon, or scrambled eggs and ham or something, and hot biscuits.
And they had the scrambled eggs, which were powdered,
Lend-Lease eggs.
They had some fried spam, which we went off and left a lot of times in combat.
And they had some dried biscuits that they served us.
And it charges three pounds per serving.
My goodness.
Which is about, then is about $6.50.
So they took advantage of us.
And after all, that old boy that served them had probably
got them in the black market.
And they were given to some English army unit as rations.
And they found a way into the black market, into this cafe, downstairs cafe.
And they charged six and a half a serving for them.
Well, you don't know these things till after he brings it out there.
You don't stop and ask for a price if Hungary's talking it out.
You find a place you can buy something to eat, you buy it, and then cuss it when you leave there because they're taking advantage of you.
So they would take advantage of you.
But the people that you dealt with normally were very friendly people.
Now, let's go back to the problem of refugees, which we started.
Tell me about that again.
Well, the refugees, or we call them DPs, displaced people, displaced persons, they have been used as slave labor.
They were in a compound.
They slept bunkered beds four or five high, jammed just as tight as you could jam them so that people could get through them, men and women
intermixed, families intermixed, so that there was no privacy, no capability of privacy at all.
It was just a existence, a bare existence, and they gave them enough food to give them energy to do the labor.
If they weren't doing useful labor, well, they didn't get any food.
It was just that simple.
And
These two, these, did you get the part about the two Dutch boys?
No, we were just going, why don't you go ahead with that?
Okay.
Because that's where we noticed that there was something wrong.
Okay, back in Germany, during combat, we were around Aachen, Gallenkirchen, in that part of Germany, just getting into Germany.
We, we passed a town, and I guess it was part of the, the Dortmund complex.
We were pretty close there, maybe ten miles from it.
There was a Messerschmitt plant.
And these two Dutch boys had been going to a vocational high school, which was a postgraduate high school.
They'd been to normal high school in Amsterdam.
And one of them was taking woodworking, and the other was taking accounting vocation.
And their names were Case and Garrett.
I don't know.
That's the way you pronounce it anyway.

both of them talked six or seven languages, which they have to in the normal business commercial world there, they learn this, because they'll be trading with a German in one minute, and an Englishman the next, and a Frenchman the next, and a Dutchman the next time, and so their education requirements are that they take every language spoken on the European continent, and these two boys have mastered
including Russian and including the Slavic dialects.
They were good translators.
So I got the idea of relieving my...
I had a German-born boy who was a sergeant in the American Army.
He came over as a youngster with his family, Sergeant Anderson.
And I used his interpreter, talking with Germans, and I used...
him with these people until I got their confidence, until they got my confidence, let's say it that way.
But I took them on thinking originally that I would put them down there and doing KP in the men's mess, relieve our soldiers of that sort.
And all it cost was food, and so that was cheap.
You didn't have to pay them any?
No, no, we didn't pay them anything.
We just took them under our care.

Now they didn't want to go back to Amsterdam because they learned through their grapevine that the Dutch army was sending all able-bodied soldiers to the Dutch East Indies because they had an uprising out there and they were gathering all these people up, putting them in the army and sending them to suppress the troubles they had out in the Dutch East Indies.
Those boys weren't interested in going home.
They didn't want any part of that.
And they knew that they could eat in my battalion, or they could eat in the American Army.
And so they came in and convinced us that they wanted to work for the Army.
And when I learned their language capabilities, well, I used them as interpreters, which are invaluable in these DP camps, for instance.
We talked about the treatment of them in the DP camps.
Did you give them a uniform?
Give them clothing?
Oh, no, no, no.
When we go in, and that's the point I'm working up to, their contact or their resentment of the Germans and their association with the Germans is my interpreter.
They needed some clothes.
The clothes they had were ragged ass, worn out.
And so we got in there, and I got the burgomaster in the first town after they came to us.
and told him to get these boys some clothes.
And the whole half hour, he came back and took the boys down to some clothing outfit.
And he gave them a new suit, a half dozen shirts, clean underwear, and a new pair of shoes.
And that's all there was to it.
They didn't pay for them.
But I didn't go, and so I didn't see that operation.
I know they got the clothes.
And everywhere we went, I'd tell him, go get the burgomaster.
Come in and get him a typewriter or get him an overcoat or get him a pair of rain boots.
And the burgomaster would show up with them and just give them to him.
I took them on.
I used them as interpreters in handling these DPs, which our basic responsibility was keeping them enclosed.
keeping them from going over the country foraging and looting and burning and taking reprisals against the Germans, because that's what they wanted to do and tried to do.
And very quickly, we got instructions from the higher command to stop that, which put an extra burden on our guards and all that kind of business.
But that was just one of the chores that we had to contend with.
Those two boys were invaluable to me as interpreters.
And they, after I proved them out to my own satisfaction, I used them entirely.
And they didn't have any compassion in getting information from the Germans.
Can you give me some examples?
Example?
I tried to interrogate a German about something
He wouldn't give me the information I wanted.
And I'd get up and go out of the room.
And when I came back, they had the information.
They didn't have any compassions about physical contact with them, this kind of thing.
I made it my job to not observe it, but that got the information.
And I'm sure it was by physical contact.
They stayed with me all the way down to Vienna, and then that's where I left them coming back this way.
One time I took them on a trip down to Salzburg.
I didn't want to see Salzburg.
We were in a little town named Alt Town about 35 miles north of Salzburg.
And I got the idea of buying my wife
hand-embroidered blouse you'd see in the windows.
Salzburg was a clothing center.
They had some very elite shops there that had beautiful clothes in the show windows.
I went in this shop and I told, Garrett was the boy, he was the older of the two, and he was doing the talking.
Told him to find out if she had any,
silk blouses and the white one.
And she didn't respond.
She didn't have any blouses.
They had one in the window, and that was all there was to it.
And of course, Garrett told me, she's lying, she's lying.
She'd give them to us, and she'd get them.
And so he took a paper box of matches, you know, what a paper full of matches is, and went over and got
grabbed the drapery, started to set the drapery on fire.
And she started screaming at him, come here, come here, come here.
And she took him back in the storeroom and they brought out some beautiful blouses.
But he wouldn't have had any compassion about setting that place on fire to get the point over.
They just didn't give him any compromise.
Because they'd been beat, been slaved, handled as a slave for four years.
And these were good boys.
They were good, intelligent boys.
But he wouldn't hesitate about burning that place down just to get even with them, if that's a good way to put it.
And this gal went in back in the back and got some boxes and came out.
And she asked me what size, of course, talking through Garrett.
And I couldn't tell her size, but I saw one about my wife's size.
And I just said, I want to fit that woman there.
She came up with it, and my wife still got it.
It's a beautiful thing.
All hand embroidered, and oh, it's a beautiful thing.
And I think it cost me $78.
I don't remember any marks and all this kind of business, but I just reflected it's $78, which is most reasonable.
It was a very stylish thing, very stylish, and beautiful embroidery with flowers.
Now what about Soviet or Russian refugees?
There must have been some.
There were lots of them, and they were the more militant of the refugees.
As a matter of fact, I got the commander of the camp in our area one time, and he was sending out raiding parties at night time.
And I got the commander, and again using Gary as my interpreter, told him very positively that this area was under martial law.
Anything that moved at night was dead.
I'd give my guards specific instructions that anything that moved after dark was dead.
And I got the point over to him.
He put out the word, and that stopped it in that particular area.
But these Russians were just going on a foraging party, meaning they'd go out and burn.
Just a reaction of liberty, I guess you'd call it.
They'd been slave labor, and they'd been beaten and so abused that their only attitude was to get even.
And they were the real troublemakers.
What was their physical condition like?
Their physical condition?
Well, the ones that could do manual labor or skillful labor were fed and they were in pretty good shape.
But the others were starving to death.
If you didn't have some capability of performing a meaningful task, meaning working in whatever factory they put you in and do a proficient job, they'd starve you to death.
And if you did, why, they gave you food, because they wanted your physical capability.
So some of them you saw were in good shape, and some of them were in pitiful shape.
Did you send them back to the Soviet Union?
No, we kept them intact in this particular area, gave them groceries, and made them take care of themselves.
And I'm sure
I wasn't a part of it, but I'm sure they were eventually put on trains and sent back to Russia as soon as the G-5s got in.
The G-5s is the military government end of the Army, like G-1, 2, 3, 4.
The G-5 is the military government.
And those are the people that came on and took charge of them after the combat troops went on by them.
They put them through their classification interviews, meaning were they collaborators, were they Nazis, or this is what they were looking for.
And they all proved out why.
I'm sure they went back to Russia.
They put them on trains and got rid of them as fast as they could to relieve us of the responsibility of feeding them.
And that was the first responsibility.
Oh.
Now, your active duty ended in 1946, right after.
In June of 46, if I remember.
Right after this was your last job as chief of public works and utility, as far as the active duty was concerned.
Before we go into your reserve duty, is there anything else that you'd like to talk about?
Are there any other episodes, you think?
After I left the US forces in Austria,
up to heading home, and that's where I got command of the 94th Division Artillery.
Right.
After you left Austria, okay, and where was that located, Germany?
Yeah, Bad Abling.
I got the order right here.
Bad Abling.
They had A-I-B-L-I-N-G, Germany, where I was put in command of the 94th Divorce Army, and here's where I assumed command on 18 December, 1945.
That's when I took command of that.
Why did they give you that command after the war was over?
Well, this was a staging command of...
keeping the first preservation of the equipment and keeping the soldiers busy until we could ship them home.
That was our main chore of keeping them busy, getting them to rest camps, getting them back, categorizing them, meaning the high point people got home first, and general

occupation duties, meaning traffic control and control of the local city government, meaning keeping your finger on the burgomaster to make him react to our peacetime approach to things rather than combat war.
What about the denazification program?
G5 people.
Oh, okay.
So you were not involved without that.
Well, only in the effect of implementing it.
If they had any troubles, we came in.
But basically, the military government people came in and set themselves as a supervisor of the civilian population and government.
And all we did, we did traffic control work, we did...

security work, and there were still pockets of German, me and an isolated German that resented us, and he would take a pot shot at an American down in the end or throw a hand grenade out of a window at nighttime or something like that.
Even in 1946?
Even in 1946, that's right.
And there's where we came into that.
When that happened, well, we moved in and we tried to get, put a finger on it.
But
Our whole job then was occupation and keeping our people busy, keeping our soldiers busy.
Sponsoring competitions and ball games and this kind of thing.
Now you must have had a heck of a lot of points.
And you must have been one, since you've been in since 1940, you must have been one
very high on being able to go back to the States.
Why weren't you sent immediately home?
Well, that's another interesting story.
And that's one of those things that I tried to buck and couldn't accomplish.
I did have more points than anybody in the battalion.
I should have been number one on the list to come home after the combat after VE day.
And they had us set up to go through the
Japanese island deal, and then VJ Day caught us, and I went down to the 2 Corps, which is headquarters in Salzburg, to see the G2 as a personnel officer, two-star general.
I went down there, I'm going home.
I'm going to get out of this man's army and go make some money.
And he said, I don't have anything on you, kid.
You got a job.
Just keep on doing like you are.
And he gave me that for a month.
And I kept making a nuisance of myself, thinking that the squeaky wheel would get the grease.
And I passed him in the hall one day.
And he said, come in here, kid.
Well, I saw something on you yesterday.
And he looked through his desk, worst looking mind, and gave it to me.
Here it is.
You're going to Vienna tomorrow.
I said, oh, General, there's something wrong.
There's a misunderstanding here somewhere.
He looked over his eyes and glanced at me and said, yeah, kid, well, you have something that's wrong.
You're going to Vienna tomorrow.
You're not going home.
And he told me, and of course, I don't believe him to this day, that I was the only civil engineer officer, lieutenant colonel,
The II Corps.
II Corps was all the western half of Austria.
Went all the way down to Glens, which is probably the big half, 60% of Austria, were the soldiers in II Corps.
And I know, in my own mind, I wasn't the only civil engineer lieutenant colonel.
running through the 66-1, which is your personnel card.
And that shows your qualifications.
And I was the first one that this warrant officer was going through the card looking for one.
Came on it, and he said, here he is, General.
Write the order.
And that's it.
And of course, I told General McMahon, that's something bad wrong here, General.
He said, yep, Kidwell, that's right.
You were wrong.
You're going to be here tomorrow.
And of course,
All I could do was be a good soldier and go.
And I thoroughly enjoyed it.
It was well worth the seven, eight months I was down there.
Because Austria is a beautiful country, and I've made a lot of good acquaintances there.
I saw some gorgeous country, and I accomplished something.
We got the power plants running to some degree.
We got juice back into the major cities and some of the little country towns.
So I felt that I accomplished something.
So I don't regret it.
It just took six, seven, eight months more of my life away and I'm nothing worse for it I guess.
Okay, then after that you went up to the company commander or the CO of the 94th Artillery?
Division Artillery, right.
And you were there until July?
Right.
June of 1946.
At about that time you were promoted to full colonel, weren't you?
Excuse me, please.
Now let's continue on your promotion of colonel.
Okay.
I was promoted when I was in the 94th
the colonel, somewhere in there.
I cannot get the exact date of it.
On 10 February 1946, I was promoted to chicken colonel, full colonel.
And then I retired in June, I believe.
Now, why were you promoted?
Because of your record, obviously.
Because of my record and my longevity and my Army education and qualifications.
And actually, the Departee Command job is the Brigadier General's job.
And there I was doing it as Lieutenant Colonel.
And the CG, as soon as I impressed on him that I knew what I was doing and got about doing his job and didn't give him any problems, he was kind enough to recommend me for a motion.
I got it.
Great.
Purely and simply, I impressed him.
And it was within his, well, it was his responsibility.
He's supposed to do that.
And the TO job was there.
I mean, table of organization.
I was holding a brigadier general's job.
And all he could do was promote me to colonel.
And a commanding general.
Was he a two star?
Oh, yeah, he was two-star general.
I forget who it was.
Oh, his name was General Anderson.
I remember that now.
He was, I don't remember his first name, but he was major general.
And how long did you stay in that post?
Well, until I got home, and I actually brought the 94th Division artillery home.
Oh, yeah, you brought it home with you.
Brought it home, and we dispersed up at Camp Kilmer, New York, and...
I always went scattered like a covered quail.
Now, were you happy to get out of active duty, or did you think as a full colonel that maybe you might want to stay in the service?
I had innumerable high-ranking good friends encourage me to stay in service.
And as a full colonel, I could have done very well, I'm sure.
On the other hand,
the Army that I had seen up until that time was not conducive to the life I wanted to live.
Meaning, I think in the first three years of our life in the Army, from December of 40, when I went in until I shipped overseas, I was moved 13 or 14 times
And of course, moving like that, you become a gypsy, meaning you don't have any place to plant your roots.
Housing is hell around an army camp.
And I didn't have enough seniority to get quarters on the post or being a new man.
If I was a lieutenant colonel, I was still at the bottom of the totem pole because
people ahead of me to get them.
And we were living in rooms that, frankly, bear existence.
And some places, Fort Meade, for instance, I got home on Saturday night every other week if there wasn't anything important going on.
Otherwise, I skipped two more weeks.
I couldn't project myself wanting that kind of life for 30 years.
And I had the pressure put on me by a lot of high-ranking people to stay in.
What a good life it would be and all that kind of business.
On the other hand, I had a civil engineering education, and I wanted to get back and start making some money.
And there's two ends of the pendulum.
And I had to make a decision, and I decided to get out, stay in reserves, and stay qualified.
Now let's talk about the reserves.
Let's talk about the very first assignment you had.
You came back to Dallas, right?
And then you decided to- OK, I got to change files here now, because I'm not ETO.
This is where I separated New York.
Now I get the next file here.
Okay, we came back to Dallas, and I got in touch with the local reserve people, or TMD they called it, Texas Military District people, and they assigned me to, I believe it was a core artillery,
I'll find it in a minute here.
You were the executive officer of the 90th Infantry Division Artillery, according to the secret.
Well, okay.
That's correct.
I was assigned to the 9th Division Artillery, Headquarters and Headquarters Battery.
as executive officer.
And I stayed there for, Colonel John Mayo was the, was the commanding officer.
And what were your functions as VXO?
As the executive officer, I...
I know what you do as the executive, but I mean, that wasn't a good question.
I meant, what did the division do?
It's a training division.
Okay.
In other words...
Located here in Dallas?
The headquarters is located here in Dallas, and they had a battalion in Amarillo and a battalion in College Station, a battalion in San Antonio, a battalion in Beaumont,
Those poor battalions.
And our function was to train the enlisted recruits to be proficient in their job as a reservist.
Now, they could beat the draft by joining a reserve unit.
That was an incentive to join a reserve unit, actually.
And we took a man when he got to be 18 or just before he got drafted, he'd come join a reserve unit to beat it.
They got an advance notice of a couple of weeks or something like that that they were going to be drafted on some date two weeks from now.
And if they joined a unit while they didn't get drafted, the draft board would accept them.
What did that mean for the quality of soldiers enlisted in the mountain?

Well, of course, that was across the board at that time, meaning you got your share of high school dropouts, you got your share of high school students, you got your share of high school graduates, and you got your share of college graduates.
Not graduates, but college students.
So you got a cross-section of American life and...
We had some mighty good men.
Well, of course, some of them would be very good, but was there sort of a, if they're, part of the reason they're joining is to avoid the draft, were they in some respects anti-military?
No, no, no, no, no, no.
They weren't taking exemptions by claiming 4F, for instance, if they have physical disability or religious scruples or something like that.
They wanted to continue their pursuit of education or their job or something.
And the law said that they could join a reserve unit or National Guard and fulfill their military obligation.
And so...
they had the option of joining a reserve unit or being drafted.
Now, the powerful incentive is to join a reserve unit, but some of them did, some of them didn't.
But they made good soldiers.
They eagerly learned, and it was a training mission for us.
We went to active duty two weeks every year, either at Fort Sill or down at Fort Sam Houston out at Camp Bullis to do our firing.
The last three years, as I remember, we went to Fort Hood, where we could use air range up there.
And I'd been CO of the 9th Divardy.
I believe it was after the end of my second camp with them, I got the idea of setting our goals to be combat proficient.
meaning that each battalion had to pass the basic battalion test, combat proficiency test, that every unit that went to combat overseas had to pass before they were certified combat proficient.
Isn't that quite a demand to make on reservists?
Well, no more so than that.
a normal army unit.
I've set my heart and mind of making the 90th and Duvarty equal to any regular army unit.
And I did.
The first year, two of my four battalions passed the combat proficiency test.
That was Colonel Coconose and Colonel Butler's battalion.
Both of them became generals.
That's right.
And this is part of the reason why.
That was the third year.
The fourth year I was commander, three of the units passed.
And my last year, all four of my units passed, which means my battalion could have been certified by a testing team, an army testing team, as proficient to go into combat.
And that's the ultimate of training.
General Rudder just told me I was pipe dreaming when I told him what my long-range plans were.
But he couldn't have been more pleased when we passed with all four battalions my last year.
And to me, that was...
the ultimate of training.
That's a real accomplishment.
Really, it was.
It was a lot of work.
Certainly, I couldn't have done it without superior battalion commanders and superior battery commanders.
Let's talk about a couple of those.
Tell me about Kokonos and Butler.
Well, they were outstanding gentlemen.
